Polaris Bank Limited has reported a profit before tax (PBT) of N27.8billion for its first full year operations. The first full year financial result indicated that the lender posted gross earnings of N150.8 billion and a Profit Before Tax (PBT) of N27.8billion during the year in review. According to the financial statements report released at the weekend, the bank also closed the 2019 financial year with total assets of N1.1trillion and shareholders’ funds of N83 billion. The result further shows that the bank’s 14% Capital Adequacy Ratio and 81% Liquidity Ratio were above regulatory requirements, demonstrating strong prudential compliance and strong capital buffer, careful liquidity management and resilience. The bank’s customer deposits stood at N857.9billion even as the Bank continues to focus on stable, low-cost deposits and well-diversified portfolio devoid of high concentration. Likewise, the loan book stood at N261billion providing the Bank with the desired headroom to accommodate required growth in risk assets to support the nation’s economic growth. Commenting on the bank’s performance, the Managing Director, Mr. Adetokunbo Abiru said that: “the emergence of Polaris Bank on September 21, 2018, has heralded a new dawn as it laid the foundation for institutional competitiveness and service innovation in the nation’s challenging banking space.” Zenith Bank’s PBT of N232bn excites shareholders FCMB Group reports N188bn revenue, N20.1bn profit UK grants FCMB full commercial bank status